450. Bogeon sahoe nonjib. 1990 Dec;10(2):57-8.

A cohort analysis of phasic changes in family life cycle as basis for family 
health studies (summary).

Park IH, Kim JK.

PIP: Researchers used data from South Korea's 1986 National Sample Survey on 
Family Life Cycle (FLC) on 2644 women married between 1945-1984 and their 
families to analyze phasic changes in the FLC. Both mortality and fertility fell 
resulting in a shortening of the family expansion period (formation [I], 
extension [II], and contraction [IV] phases) and a lengthening of the empty nest 
and widowhood periods (completed extension [III], completed contraction [V], and 
dissolution phases [VI]). Phases I-II for those married between 1945-1854 stood 
at 14.7 years and a median marriage age of 18.1 compared to 3.1 years for those 
married between 1975-1984 and median marriage age of 23. In addition, phase III 
took 13.1 years for the earlier cohort which had a median age of 32.8 at last 
birth whereas, for the later cohort, it took 24.2 years and the median age at 
last birth stood at 26.1. Phase IV averaged 12.4 years for the 1945-1954 
marriage cohort with a mean age of 45.9 at the time of 1st child's marriage, but 
it fell to 2.1 years for the 1975-1984 cohort and mean age was 50.3. Phases V-VI 
stood at 5.4 years for the earlier cohort and the mean age was 58.3 at the time 
of last child's marriage whereas the corresponding figures for the later cohort 
were 22.2 years and 52.4. The termination of family formation phase was 
associated with age at marriage and family type while the extension phase was 
associated with family type, age at 1st birth, and number of children ever born. 
These results indicated a need to switch family planning and maternal and child 
health services from quantitatively orientation to qualitatively orientation. 
The public sector should emphasize preventive and promotive health services. In 
addition, community health services should be developed and strengthened to 
provide comprehensive health services, e.g., chronic disease care, for the aged.

